---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "How do I open the Flutter Widget Inspector?",
    answer: "The Widget Inspector is built into Flutter DevTools. Run your app in debug mode with 'flutter run', then open DevTools by clicking the DevTools link printed in the terminal, or by running 'flutter pub global run devtools' in a separate terminal. In VS Code, click the Flutter DevTools icon in the status bar or use the command palette ('Flutter: Open DevTools'). In Android Studio, click the 'Open DevTools' button in the Flutter Inspector panel."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the Layout Explorer and when should I use it?",
    answer: "The Layout Explorer is a sub-panel within the Widget Inspector that visualizes flex layout (Row, Column, Flex) constraints and sizing. Use it when debugging layout overflow errors, understanding why a widget takes a certain size, or figuring out flex factor distribution. Select any Row/Column widget in the tree and the Layout Explorer shows each child's flex value, the available space, and how space is allocated — much faster than adding debug borders manually."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I find which widget is causing a RenderFlex overflow?",
    answer: "When a yellow-and-black stripe overflow error appears, open the Widget Inspector and enable 'Select Widget Mode' (the cursor icon). Click the overflowing area on the device/emulator screen. The inspector will highlight the responsible widget in the tree. Then open the Layout Explorer to see the exact pixel measurements. Common fixes include wrapping children in Expanded/Flexible, adding SingleChildScrollView, or reducing padding/margin values."
  },
  {
    question: "What does the Performance Overlay show?",
    answer: "The Performance Overlay (enabled via 'flutter run --profile' or through DevTools) shows two graphs: the top graph represents the GPU thread (rasterization time) and the bottom represents the UI thread (Dart code execution time). Each bar should stay below 16ms for 60fps or 8ms for 120fps rendering. Red bars indicate a frame took too long. Use this to identify whether jank is caused by expensive build methods (UI thread) or complex painting/shaders (GPU thread)."
  },
  {
    question: "How do I debug widget rebuilds in Flutter?",
    answer: "Enable the 'Track Widget Rebuilds' feature in DevTools to highlight widgets that rebuild on each frame. You can also add debugPrintRebuildDirtyWidgets = true; to your main() function to log rebuilds to the console. To reduce unnecessary rebuilds, use const constructors wherever possible, extract frequently-rebuilding subtrees into separate widgets, and use ValueListenableBuilder or Selector (with Provider) instead of rebuilding entire widget trees."
  },
  {
    question: "Can I use the Widget Inspector on a release build?",
    answer: "No. The Widget Inspector, DevTools, and most debugging overlays only work in debug and profile modes. Release builds strip out all debugging information and observatory ports for performance and security reasons. For performance profiling in conditions closer to production, use 'flutter run --profile' which removes debug assertions but retains profiling hooks. For production crash analysis, integrate a crash reporting service like Firebase Crashlytics or Sentry."
  }
];
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Flutter Widget Inspector — Widget Tree Inspector Guide"
  description="Complete guide to Flutter's Widget Inspector: widget tree exploration, Layout Explorer, performance overlay, and debugging rendering issues with Flutter DevTools."
  tool="flutter-widget-inspector"
  faq={faq}
>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Flutter Widget Inspector</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">Master Flutter DevTools' Widget Inspector to explore widget trees, debug layout issues, analyze performance, and fix rendering problems on iOS and Android.</p>
  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span>✅ Widget Tree Exploration</span>
    <span>✅ Layout Explorer</span>
    <span>✅ Performance Overlay</span>
    <span>✅ Rebuild Tracking</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Introduction to Flutter DevTools</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Flutter DevTools is a suite of performance and debugging tools for Dart and Flutter applications. The Widget Inspector is the most-used component — it gives you a live, interactive view of the widget tree running on your device or emulator, letting you inspect properties, visualize layout constraints, and identify performance bottlenecks without adding debug print statements to your code.</p>
  <p class="mb-4">Unlike a static view, the inspector is live: as you navigate your app, the widget tree updates in real time. Selecting a widget on the device highlights it in the tree, and selecting a node in the tree highlights it on the device — making it easy to map visual elements to their code representations.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Setting Up Flutter DevTools</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">DevTools ships with the Flutter SDK. To ensure you have the latest version, update it globally:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-sm"># Update Flutter (includes DevTools)
flutter upgrade

# Or run DevTools directly from pub global
dart pub global activate devtools
dart pub global run devtools

# Launch your app in debug mode first
flutter run -d chrome          # for web
flutter run -d emulator-5554   # for specific Android emulator
flutter run -d "iPhone 15"     # for iOS simulator</code></pre>
  <p class="mb-4">Once your app is running, the terminal prints a URL like <code>http://127.0.0.1:9100?uri=...</code>. Open that URL in Chrome to launch DevTools. The Widget Inspector tab is the first panel you'll see.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Navigating the Widget Tree</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">The widget tree panel displays your app's widget hierarchy as a collapsible tree. Each node shows the widget type and, for many widgets, a summary of key properties. There are two modes for selecting widgets:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4 space-y-1">
    <li><strong>Select Widget Mode</strong> — Click the cursor icon, then tap any element on the device screen to jump to that widget in the tree.</li>
    <li><strong>Tree Navigation</strong> — Expand nodes manually in the tree panel to find widgets by hierarchy.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="mb-4">When you select a widget, the right-side panel shows its properties. For a Text widget you'll see the style, overflow behavior, and text data. For a Container you'll see decoration, padding, margin, and constraints. This is faster than reading the source code, especially in large component libraries.</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-sm">// Example: a widget tree you might inspect
Scaffold
  └── Column
        ├── AppBar(title: Text('Home'))
        ├── Expanded
        │     └── ListView.builder(itemCount: 20)
        │           └── ListTile(title: Text('Item'), ...)
        └── FloatingActionButton(onPressed: ...)</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Using the Layout Explorer</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">The Layout Explorer is invaluable for understanding Flutter's constraint-based layout system. Select any Row, Column, Flex, or Stack widget to open a visual representation of its layout:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4 space-y-1">
    <li>Each child's flex factor, minimum size, and actual rendered size are displayed</li>
    <li>The main axis and cross axis are labeled with arrow indicators</li>
    <li>You can see exactly how much space is available vs. consumed</li>
    <li>Overflow is shown in red before it causes a runtime error</li>
  </ul>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-sm">// Common layout issue: unbounded width in a Row
Row(
  children: [
    Text('Left label'),
    // This Text will overflow if the string is long:
    Text(someLongDynamicString),
  ],
)

// Fix: wrap in Expanded to give it a bounded constraint
Row(
  children: [
    Text('Left label'),
    Expanded(child: Text(someLongDynamicString, overflow: TextOverflow.ellipsis)),
  ],
)</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Performance Overlay and Frame Analysis</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">To analyze rendering performance, enable the performance overlay. This works best in profile mode which removes debug overhead but keeps profiling hooks:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-sm"># Run in profile mode for realistic performance data
flutter run --profile

# Alternatively, enable overlay programmatically during development:
MaterialApp(
  showPerformanceOverlay: true, // shows UI and GPU thread graphs
  checkerboardRasterCacheImages: true, // highlights cached images
  checkerboardOffscreenLayers: true,   // highlights offscreen layers
  home: MyHomePage(),
)</code></pre>
  <p class="mb-4">Common performance issues identified through the overlay:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside mb-4 space-y-1">
    <li><strong>Expensive build methods</strong> — UI thread spikes; refactor with const constructors or extract subtrees</li>
    <li><strong>Shader compilation jank</strong> — GPU thread spike on first render; use SkSL warmup or impeller</li>
    <li><strong>Non-constant animations</strong> — Ensure AnimationController is only calling setState on the minimal subtree</li>
    <li><strong>Heavy image decoding</strong> — Use precacheImage() for images loaded in advance</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Debugging Rendering Issues</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Flutter's debug mode provides visual aids to identify rendering problems without DevTools:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-sm">import 'package:flutter/rendering.dart';

void main() {
  // Show widget boundaries with colored borders
  debugPaintSizeEnabled = true;

  // Show baseline alignment guidelines
  debugPaintBaselinesEnabled = true;

  // Show pointer event hit test areas
  debugPaintPointersEnabled = true;

  // Log render tree to console
  debugDumpRenderTree();

  // Log widget tree to console
  debugDumpApp();

  runApp(const MyApp());
}</code></pre>
  <p class="mb-4">For clipping and overflow issues, the <code>debugPaintSizeEnabled</code> flag draws colored borders around every widget, making it immediately obvious which widget is responsible for a layout that doesn't look right visually.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Tracking Widget Rebuilds</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">Excessive widget rebuilds are a common source of Flutter performance issues. DevTools' "Track Rebuilds" feature flashes widgets that rebuild each frame. Enable it from the Widget Inspector toolbar. Programmatically, you can also add logging:</p>
  <pre class="bg-surface rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4"><code class="text-sm">// In main(), enable rebuild logging
import 'package:flutter/foundation.dart';

void main() {
  debugPrintRebuildDirtyWidgets = true; // logs every dirty widget
  runApp(const MyApp());
}

// Use const constructors to prevent unnecessary rebuilds
class MyWidget extends StatelessWidget {
  const MyWidget({super.key}); // const constructor = no rebuild if params unchanged

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return const Padding(
      padding: EdgeInsets.all(16.0), // const = no allocation per build
      child: Text('Hello'),          // const = no rebuild
    );
  }
}</code></pre>

  <AdUnit slot="auto" format="auto" label="Advertisement" />
  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
  <ToolPageCta currentTool="flutter-widget-inspector" relatedTags={['flutter', 'mobile', 'dart', 'debugging', 'ui', 'widgets']} />
</BaseLayout>
